<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-169-080  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 169 080.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  March 1989 v36 n3 p30(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Personal computers tackle batch control.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pinto, James J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ruggedized microcomputers are more and more replacing programmablecontrollers (PLCs) for industrial batch control functions.andP;  Themajor difference between office and factory automation is in I-O,which consists of alphanumeric data in the office but real-time,real-world variables, such as temperature, weight or volume, onthe factory floor.andP;  PC-based software is available thatencompasses all the functional requirements of industrial batchprocessing and expert systems allow relatively small computersystems to provide expert analysis, diagnosis, advisory servicesand heuristically-based control, complementing, rather thaneliminating human labor, and enhancing the capabilities ofproduction workers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersProcess ControlBatch ProcessingControllers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   Block diagram of typical coffee-blending batching system. (chart)Networked PCs in the industrial batching environment. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>